> Barramundi is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Trim, peel, and cut @carrots{12%ounce} on a diagonal into ½-inch-thick pieces. Finely chop @cilantro{1/4%ounce}. Zest and quarter @lemon{1%unit}. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}.

Toss carrots on a foil-lined #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon}, @salt{pinch}, and @pepper{pinch}. Roast on top rack until golden brown and softened, ~{20-25%minutes}.

While carrots roast, in a #small bowl{}, combine cilantro, half the @cumin{1%teaspoon} (you'll use the rest later), half the lemon zest, @olive oil{2%tablespoon}, a big squeeze of lemon juice, and a pinch of garlic to taste. Season with salt, pepper, and @chili flakes{1%teaspoon} to taste.

Heat @butter{1%tablespoon} in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add @Israeli couscous{2.5%ounce} and remaining garlic. Cook, stirring often, until garlic is fragrant and couscous is lightly toasted, ~{1-2%minutes}. Stir in @water{3/4%cup} and @veggie stock concentrate{1%unit}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until al dente, ~{6-8%minutes}. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

While couscous cooks, pat @barramundi{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}. Season all over with remaining cumin, salt, and pepper. Heat a drizzle of olive oil in a large, preferably nonstick, pan over medium-high heat. Add barramundi and cook until opaque and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes} per side. Turn off heat.

Fluff couscous with a #fork{}; season with salt and pepper. Toss carrots with remaining lemon zest. Divide couscous, carrots, and barramundi between plates. Top barramundi with cilantro sauce. Serve with remaining lemon wedges on the side.